WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.560
Hey everybody, we're back with another podcast and it's been a while since we've done one, but

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:10.640
during the last Global Town Hall, we got a lot of questions around compensation and really more

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:15.600
than we could handle in the Town Hall. So we wanted to come back where we had a little more time.

00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:20.320
I brought Holly with me and we want to try to answer more of those questions. So today,

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:26.960
we're going to share as much as we can about the comp cycle, but also about what our oceanary

00:00:26.960 --> 00:00:32.880
philosophy is on compensation and also what we're doing to address this volatile time in the labor

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:40.000
markets as we focus on a, you know, very fortunately a growing business. I don't know if we're going to

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.840
resolve everybody's concerns today, but maybe by putting some light on it, we're going to be able

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:52.320
to help a little bit. It's really a personal topic. It's more than just a paycheck. It's a measure of

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:59.440
the appreciation for your efforts and what you do. It's your ability to provide safety and help

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:05.040
provide for your family. It's a sense of security and especially when the world around us is so

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:11.680
uncertain. Compensation is only one element of the employee value proposition that we offer,

00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:17.200
but it is a very important element. And let me jump in there, Holly, you know, beyond salary and

00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:21.520
wages, I think the total value of working for oceanary includes a lot of things. It includes

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:26.720
our health plans, time off and our other benefits, as well as opportunities for advancement,

00:01:27.520 --> 00:01:32.479
hybrid work where it makes sense and the culture and experience of working with people who are

00:01:32.479 --> 00:01:37.280
among the best in the business. And we have a reputation for being able to attract these

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:43.360
outstanding people across all of the businesses we work in. And that's a pretty broad range,

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:50.080
but that ability to attract and retain and motivate people, it has to happen with more than just the

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:56.640
paycheck. That said, though, in my career as an HR professional, it's what's on your paycheck.

00:01:56.640 --> 00:02:03.280
He's always number one. Very good point. So let's start there because I think compensation really is

00:02:03.280 --> 00:02:08.720
top of mind for everybody. So let's talk about that first. You know, in the last town hall,

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:12.960
we did announce that we were going to have a merit program and that would be effective at the

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:17.520
beginning of August. And then right after the meeting, which we didn't talk about in the town

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:22.080
hall, was we met with Ben and Martin to review increases to the salary structure rates for the

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:29.760
SSR and OPG technicians. And that will be effective in July. So over the last two years, we've seen

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:35.920
some really unprecedented events in terms of the global workforce. And I suspect a lot of people

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:40.080
are asking themselves with all these things going on, why didn't we announce something sooner?

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:45.200
And why didn't we let people know what's going on in the process and what we're doing to make decisions

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:50.959
on the compensation structures and plans? But there was a lot going on. So Holly, maybe you

00:02:50.959 --> 00:02:56.239
can elaborate a little bit on what the process was. Let's talk about Oceanary's philosophy on

00:02:56.239 --> 00:03:02.239
compensation. You know, our philosophy is that we want people to be paid fairly, that we want them

00:03:02.239 --> 00:03:09.280
to be compensated fairly for what they do as it compares relative to both those doing similar

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:15.760
roles within the organization, but also externally. We want to remain competitive in the markets and

00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:21.520
geographies that we work in. So it starts with gathering information, gathering data about how

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:26.560
people in similar roles are paid. You can't just call up a company and ask them what they pay,

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:33.840
they likely won't tell you. And you know, we don't and won't work with our competitors to fix prices

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:38.960
or salaries or benefits. It's just not the right thing to do. And it's not legal. So we work with

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:46.000
third parties. And those third parties specialize in gathering the information and recording and

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:52.640
analyzing the information. And they usually do that gathering in the April May timeframe.

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:59.520
Once they gather the data from the companies, they mass the data, analyze the data and then report

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:05.600
back and they give you both specific and comprehensive data for jobs, job families,

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:09.519
and they also look at the overall trends of what's happening in the market.

00:04:10.079 --> 00:04:17.120
So we use this data to look at job families and to assess how close or how far we are from what

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:24.480
we're seeing at within the market. And we can also look at it to see what we expect to happen in the

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:31.440
next six to eight months. So this helps us answer two questions. Where are we relative to the market

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:37.520
and how much is the market moving? And well, you know, it's not an exact science. There's a

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:45.120
lot of art that comes into compensation. We're able to use the survey data to develop a projection

00:04:45.120 --> 00:04:50.800
about what our compensation targets should be. When I talk about an art, for example,

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:56.800
you could be in an IT role and exactly what you do in an IT role doesn't match exactly what somebody

00:04:56.800 --> 00:05:04.400
else does in a competitor's IT role, but they do require similar education, similar experience,

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:09.200
similar skill level. So you can make it comparable. So that's the art of it.

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:16.880
In some areas, there are jobs that might be in higher demand or other unique circumstances

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:21.920
that we might have to address for. In a perfect world, we're going to be doing this every year

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:27.440
and we're going to be making adjustments as they're needed. Or we can age data based on

00:05:28.560 --> 00:05:34.400
the time that's gone since the last time we got our data. But with something as seismic as a

00:05:34.400 --> 00:05:41.280
pandemic, which is what we saw, we've seen ships in the labor market that made gathering really

00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:49.200
reliable data extremely difficult in addition to impacting the dynamics that enable us to accurately

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:56.240
age the data. So in 2020, we, as well as other organizations, decided not to participate in these

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:03.440
survey processes. So it wasn't until the end of 2021 when we actually got a refreshed look at the

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:09.360
data from those third company providers. That's probably more information than anybody wanted to

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:15.680
know on the process that we go through. But we've had instances where people bring us data, like from

00:06:15.680 --> 00:06:22.320
glass door or information that they got from their neighbor. And while that is one piece of data,

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:28.720
it really requires more than that. And it requires some level of validation, which is what we count on

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:34.480
those third parties to do. I think it's important for people to understand that we do follow a

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:40.880
process and that it is data-centric, that there are quality controls through the use of these

00:06:40.880 --> 00:06:48.159
third parties and their analysis so that the decisions that we make on compensation are

00:06:48.159 --> 00:06:54.080
thorough, they're fair, they're competitive, and in the best interests of both the individuals and

00:06:54.080 --> 00:07:00.240
the company. That's a lot. And I don't think most people understand, at least not the people that

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:05.280
aren't directly involved in the process. They don't understand just how complex that is. And

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:10.480
thanks for going through that. And even with all you said, you didn't really even get into the part

00:07:10.960 --> 00:07:16.160
we have different groups working across different geographies. And in every one of those geographies,

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:22.720
a lot of them have regulatory requirements. And that tells us how overtime is treated, time off,

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:28.160
workers comp, all of that has to be factored in. Plus, there's tax implications for the company

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:34.320
and for the individuals. So it is a complex process. And I think you did a really great job of

00:07:34.320 --> 00:07:39.920
talking about the process. But now maybe we can talk to people about what they can expect over

00:07:39.920 --> 00:07:47.680
the next couple of months. Absolutely. So for our employees that are paid on a day rate, those are

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:53.840
primarily our technicians, we've been undertaking a comprehensive review of both their pay rates

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:58.560
and the structure of their pay. Just for an example, to show the complexity, we have over

00:07:58.560 --> 00:08:04.720
5000 technicians that are employed across the globe in 20 different, they're paid in 20 different

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:11.040
currencies. And we have dozens of pay structures. So we've been spending a lot of time looking at

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:16.000
that data. Let me go ahead and share some of the things that have already happened before I get into

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:21.520
some of the things that are going to happen. So I'm going to go back to last summer, we redesigned

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:27.520
the pay structure for technicians in Mexico. And then if you look at the back half of last year,

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:33.680
you'd see that we increased the rates for some of our entry and mid level technician roles in our

00:08:33.679 --> 00:08:42.000
SSR and OPG organizations. So earlier this year, we also went in and completed a pay review for the

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:48.560
rates and implemented changes for the technicians in India. And most recently, we've reviewed the

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:54.880
rates for SSR and OPG technicians across all of the competencies from entry level to more senior

00:08:54.880 --> 00:09:00.160
level, and made recommendations. Ben and Martin have approved those recommendations. And right now,

00:09:00.160 --> 00:09:06.079
we're in the process of communicating them and getting them ready to go into effect in July.

00:09:06.959 --> 00:09:12.560
My team's also in the process of reviewing the survey organization, reviewing maritime,

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:20.319
reviewing divers. And we're in the very early stages of reviewing the technicians for IMDS.

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:28.000
And where we're seeing, we're seeing where our reviews are indicating a need for adjustment in

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:34.240
many places, but that hasn't always been the case. But that is now. So that's what we're seeing.

00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:39.760
Let me talk about the people that are outside of our technician that aren't day rates. So I'm talking

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:44.560
about the other population and they're what we would call merit eligible population. That's the

00:09:44.560 --> 00:09:50.320
mechanism that we use to ensure that we maintain competitiveness in the market and that we reward

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:56.240
and retain that talent. Since I've been here, I've seen that process take place at different times

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:04.800
during the year, January, June, July. And this year, it's going to be taking place in August.

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:10.320
It can really happen at any time in the year, but most recently, those merit cycles have been

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:16.080
in the summer. And so this year, it's going to be effective in August. This date, it gives us time to

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:20.880
take the data that we got in, make those recommendations, get them approved. And then

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:26.720
we have to do the systems coding and testing. And then we have to allow the managers time to go in

00:10:26.720 --> 00:10:32.880
and plan for the increases and calibrate across their organizations. And that'll get back to us.

00:10:33.680 --> 00:10:39.840
The systems will open up for managers in July, and then people will start seeing those changes

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:47.200
to their compensation on their checks in August. So based on what we're seeing and what we got from

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:54.240
the data, we are going to and have planned for a competitively meaningful merit program

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:59.600
that also recognizes the business realities and our goal to stay competitive.

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:05.360
And that's really helpful, Holly, to talk about how the two are different, especially. But

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:09.760
let me go back to technicians for a little bit, because that's one of the areas where we've

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:16.000
probably seen the most change and the most rapid change. And think about these are the people

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:20.720
largely, a lot of these are the people that go out to the to the well site and work and

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:26.800
go back to pre pandemic, we started to see a ramp up in that activity at the customer locations

00:11:26.800 --> 00:11:31.920
and offshore, and then pandemic hit and went down again pretty rapidly. And then we started to see

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:36.400
it build up again. And now we're back in that growth mode. So this is one of those, we talk

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:41.120
about supply and demand and the pressure that puts on wages. This is one that goes up and down

00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:48.000
the fastest and the most. So a lot of people feel like when we started seeing it ramp up again,

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:52.080
we didn't react quickly enough. And I think it's good to talk about how,

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:58.160
number one, it's what we see, but it's also the competition, right? There's other people out there

00:11:58.160 --> 00:12:03.280
that their work is ramping up a little bit too. They don't have the same means to train people

00:12:03.280 --> 00:12:07.520
that we do. So they come and look for trained people at Ocean Earing. And therefore there gets

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:12.319
to be more competition for talent at that technician level. So, you know, it is hard

00:12:12.319 --> 00:12:16.880
to keep up, but maybe you could shed a little more light on that. It may feel like we're not

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:23.199
adjusting quickly enough, but there is an important distinction to differentiate between

00:12:23.199 --> 00:12:26.960
whether you're responding or whether you're reacting and you want to make sure that you're

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:32.720
making the right move. It's also important for people to be aware that if we identify a gap,

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:38.560
we move as quickly as we can, as quickly as possible to address those gaps. For our offshore

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:46.560
workforce, we saw a premium that came in at the height of the industry that was in 2014, 2015.

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:52.080
And then we saw that premium decline over time as the industry started to contract a little bit.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:58.160
We saw that start to come back only to kind of erode and go away again with the pandemic.

00:12:58.160 --> 00:13:03.520
We've got that kind of volatility within a compensation structure, within a wage structure.

00:13:04.719 --> 00:13:10.319
It does make it a little bit more challenging and it does inhibit our ability to respond as

00:13:10.319 --> 00:13:15.360
quickly as maybe people would like. You know, there is a natural tension that exists between

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:21.760
wanting to pay people as much as you can to attract and retain them, but also ensuring that we remain

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:27.760
competitive, which enables us to be able to provide sustained employment and to win work

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:33.920
from our customers. There's been a lot of work done to understand the market outlook, the macro

00:13:33.920 --> 00:13:40.960
trends, and the customer forecast. That's enabled us to make decisions about our business and how we

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:46.240
compensate and adjust wages based on what we're seeing in those trends and where we're seeing

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:52.560
the market go. I think you've done a great job of explaining sort of what's going on in the

00:13:53.199 --> 00:13:59.520
labor market and how that causes some changes and how we think about compensation. But there's

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:05.439
another painful thing going on out there and that's the big increases in the cost of living. Can you

00:14:05.439 --> 00:14:11.119
discuss a little bit about how we use that information you're getting and how we would

00:14:11.119 --> 00:14:17.599
take into consideration, how does that compare cost of living raises versus the compensation changes?

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:24.320
That's a hard question. The short answer is that it doesn't really, or at least not directly,

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:31.360
salary structures are based on the cost of labor. That labor is costed based on the industry,

00:14:31.360 --> 00:14:38.240
the market, the geography, and not the cost of living. You know, currently there are

00:14:38.800 --> 00:14:45.520
differentiation in salaries between high and low cost markets, but wages are really a function of

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:50.480
the availability of talent, supply and demand, very similar to the things that you see in supply

00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:57.439
chain. How many people are out there, the labor participation rates, how can technology substitute

00:14:57.439 --> 00:15:04.319
for labor, different things like that can impact it. The more available talent is in a particular

00:15:04.319 --> 00:15:10.079
area or for a particular job generally means that there's going to be less wage pressure on that.

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:15.760
One area where we are seeing wage pressure, for example, is in cyber. Cyber is a really hot market

00:15:15.760 --> 00:15:20.000
right now and there's less talent available than you need and we're seeing a lot of pressure in

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:27.440
that area. That just gives you an idea of supply and demand again. While we're trying, and while

00:15:27.440 --> 00:15:34.240
tying the compensation or wage increases to the cost of living sounds like a really good idea,

00:15:34.240 --> 00:15:38.400
most people really don't want to see that much volatility in their pay.

00:15:39.360 --> 00:15:45.280
There can be very dramatic changes to the inflation rate.

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:51.520
Yeah, I like that you brought that up, Holly, because it really is. I mean, we talk a lot about,

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:56.800
you know, it is very important for us to attract and retain the best people, but we also have to

00:15:56.800 --> 00:16:02.160
think about how the cost of labor is one of those costs that we need to balance to run the business.

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:09.120
And much like supply chain costs are going very high and we need to figure out how we contract

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:14.160
for materials so that we can keep our prices competitive, it's just one of those things that

00:16:14.160 --> 00:16:18.640
how we compete with the other people out there that do similar work. And some of that's going

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:26.079
to mean if we want to pay above market rates or for us to be able to afford to pay more for labor

00:16:26.079 --> 00:16:31.600
than maybe the other people are doing, then we have to have competitive costs everywhere else.

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:36.880
So it's just a balance of how much we pay for labor and all the other materials we have or that

00:16:36.880 --> 00:16:42.400
we use to go out and serve the customer. We need to be able to keep those at least close to our

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:47.360
competitors so that we can win work without losing money. And so you don't always want to win on

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:52.000
price, you want to win on differentiation. And this is where I've talked a lot about this, you know,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:57.280
technicians is the closest we have the closest correlation because they're out there. And then

00:16:57.280 --> 00:17:01.920
sometimes we get paid by the number of technicians we have in the field. So it's really easy to make

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:07.920
that comparison. But I want everybody to think about that is there are ways I mean, by less waste,

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:14.160
by less COPQ, by being able to do a better job or better technology or whatever the other things we

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:19.680
offer, then we can command a higher price and some of that higher price can come back to our team

00:17:19.680 --> 00:17:25.760
in terms of higher than average wages for the people that do the work. So I think that's something

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:31.840
that we all we all continue to think about and we all continue to work on. And it's not just one

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:36.800
thing. We don't just adjust one, we have to look at all of it in the context of how the business

00:17:36.800 --> 00:17:42.720
works. But hey, we've covered a lot, especially you, you did a lot of the heavy lifting here. But

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:50.960
since so much of this was in your court, I'm going to ask you the bill question. So if you could have

00:17:50.960 --> 00:17:54.320
one thing that everybody remembers from the podcast, what would it be?

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:04.480
It would be to remember that we want our people to be treated fairly, that it's our highest priority

00:18:05.840 --> 00:18:12.960
to build a value proposition for our employees that not only includes fair compensation

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:19.360
